#1. What happens during powered flight?

#During powered flight, the solid motor ignites and generates a peak thrust of 1600 N that easily overcomes gravity and air resistance. This massive net upward force causes the rocket to accelerate rapidly up to its maximum velocity of 227.82 m/s by the end of the burn. Meanwhile, the rocket continuously loses mass as its solid propellant burns away and escapes as high-speed exhaust gas.

#2. What happens after motor burnout?

#The moment the motor burns out at 3.9 s, the upward thrust drops to zero, and the rocket enters the coasting phase of flight. Gravity and atmospheric drag immediately begin acting as decelerating forces, rapidly slowing
the rocket's upward speed. However, due to its high upward momentum, the rocket continues to climb toward the sky while trading its kinetic energy for altitude.

#3. Why does the rocket eventually stop climbing?

#The rocket stops climbing because gravity and drag eventually deplete all of its upward kinetic energy, bringing its vertical velocity to exactly 0 m/s. The peak point of the flight is called apogee, where the vehicle reaches its maximum altitude of 3808.63 m. At this precise moment, the onboard altimeter detects the pause in ascent and triggers the deployment of the drogue parachute to begin a safe descent.
